@node editorsdesk "From The Editor's Desk"
@toc contents
============================================================================
@{b}From The Editor's Desk@{ub} - by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

As I sit here and write this I am sitting on a brand new chair, it is thanks 
to my wife's help that I was able to buy a used company chair, which are 
generally much more expensive than the ones sold on Amazon. While I have 
lived in Japan for over 17 years and learnt the lanuage up to a point, 
there is still much to learn and I will inevitably need the help my Japanese 
wife can provide. I see WhatIFF? in much the same way. While there are the 
Amiga users who have used their machines non-stop and are now Amiga wizards, 
there are others who are new to the machine, those who are returning or 
those who just need some help in recalling how to do something. WhatIFF? is 
here to help them use their Amiga better be they a new user or experienced 
user, I hope that WhatIFF? can be of help to them much like my wife has 
been a help to me when I struggle with Japanese.

This issue has some great features with some more guides on using the 
verstatile PiStorm, fixing booting errors with the A314-CP, creating 3D 
graphics with a word processor and more. We have a look at two RGB2HDMI
solutions and the latest version of the Furia. Ivan Sorensen takes us on a 
philosophical journey with the Amiga and also has some time to fit in some 
game reviews. Finally but not least we have interviews with Andy Vaisey the 
developer of the game Spheroid and who has also given us as an exclusive 
Xmas demo with 15 levels, Rob Cranley the creator of DrawerGenie and Migel 
Fides, creator of the Trinity accelerator card. And that is not all but I 
do want to keep you, so before I wrap up I just want to thank all the 
writers and contributors over this year. The magazine has grown into 
something very special thanks to your hard work. Finally thank you to 
everyone who has downloaded and read the magazine, it means a lot to hear 
your comments. Right, now I am finished! Enjoy reading the magazine and 
also don'T forget to play the Xmas demo of Spheroid, hopefully it will take 
you back to days of Amiga and winter holidays.
 
@endnode

@node shelltalk "Free For All About Anything"
@toc contents
============================================================================
@{b}Shell Talk@{ub} - by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul} 
============================================================================

Unfortunately we have not got all of our writers back on board since we 
changed from a Discord channel to a forum. So for this issue I will be 
taking over Shell Talk. And what I want to talk about is going to be quite
controversial, the PiStorm. First off I want to say that I love the PiStorm
is has made my Amiga into a super Amiga with speed beyond my imagining, RTG
support on the A1200 and hopefully networking in the future. However I had
a strange moment recently that caused me to put the PiStorm away back into
its box and put my TF1260 back in again.

About two weeks ago I was having a look at the DarkForces Amiga conversion
and was about to have it up and running on my Amiga. At the time I had the
PiStorm installed and the Amiga was flying through everything like usual.

Once the game was loaded and I started to play for a few moments, after a
short while I stopped and realised that something was missing. Usuall when
I play a 3D game or something that has been ported to the Amiga, I am
impressed. But this time there was no 'Wow!' moment, it just felt as it 
should. It then struck me that the way I viewed my Amiga now was differently
with the PiStorm installed. With the PiStorm I know that the main driver of
the CPU is a brand new RaspberryPi that is many more times powerful than any
Amiga ever made. With this also came the notion that the Amiga will of 
course be fast enough to play the game, there will not be any slow down as
my Amiga is running at something like 1.4ghz. This knowledge that my Amiga
can power through anything because it has a modern mini computer inside took
away the 'fun' element of using the Amiga. It became in other words and an
emulated Amiga and with that notion the idea that it should be able to do
anything now.

I decided to swap the PiStorm for my TF1260 and tried DarkForces again and 
it was a different experience. Most likely I did not expect or know the 060
will fly through everything as it is not a modern processor. It made the
surprise of DarkForces running well a more enjoyable experience. I do not
want to take anything away from what the PiStorm has achieved and does but
I realised it has taken some of the magic away, for me at least, of using
an Amiga. Saying that,if I had another A1200 I would put a PiStorm into it
but as I have only one A1200 the TF1260 provides a more fun and surprising
Amiga experience.

How do you feel when you run a taxing game or application with a PiStorm
vs a 'real' CPU?

@endnode

