@node rgb2hdmia600review "Hardware review: RGB2HDMI Adapters for the A600"
@toc reviews
============================================================================
@{b}Hardware Review:RGB2HDMI Adapters for the A600 @{ub} - by @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

@{b}Product Name@{ub}
RGB2HDMI
PiggyBackNotV3

@{b}Developed By@{ub}
Ian SB

@{b}Available From@{ub}
amiga-shop.net
amigstore.eu
retropassion.co.uk
progammatory.archi-tech.pl
       
@{b}Price@{ub}
25-90 EUR
  
@{b}Hardware/Software Requirements@{ub}
Amiga 600

@{b}Test Machine@{ub}
Amiga 600/3.1

@{b}Review@{ub}

The humble A600 has not had much love from WhatIFF? over the last two years
so I thought with this being our 2nd year it is time to put the A600 in the
limelight. In this review we will be looking at two varients of the RGB2HDMI
adapter: PiggyBackNot V3 and the standard board. 10 years ago I had my A600
connected to an Indivision ECS via the expansion port, this card worked
flawlessly and gave a great picture even though it was from the VGA port.

Sadly as is per usual for an Amiga user, the A600 was sold off to pay off
for some other Amiga hardware and now having obtained an A600 again I am in
the position of needing a way to get video out from my A600. While I would
like to use an Indivision again, they are very hard to come by and do not
offer the more common HDMI connector. So the RGB2HDMI seemed perfect.

What you need to consider when buying one first is if you have or want to
have an accelerator/extra ram in your A600. If so then your only choice is
the PiggyBackNot V3 or the other varients that have the flex cable. So to
begin with, let{s have a look at the PiggyBackNot V3.

@{b}PiggyBackNot V3@{ub}

Unlike the "standard" RGB2HDMI adapters the PiggyBackNot V3 from now on, 
PBNV3, does not have the Pi sitting on or close to the Denise. Instead in
a nod to the Indivision, it has the Pi sitting on a board plugged into the
expansion trapdoor port. This has the added benefit of giving you more 
space in the A600, better support for the Pi and less pressure on the Denise 
chip. The board also provides 1Mb extra chip ram, 3 clockports, a realtime 
clock chip and battery slot (Be careful how you orient the RTC chip or you
risk damaging the board). The board connects to the Denise via a flex 
cable, the adapter sits snuggly onto the Denise and clips in with a 
satisfying click. It should be noted that the connectors are not very strong
unlike the Indivision AGA, so if you remove the board more than two times it
is highly likely the adapter lose it{s tightness and you will not get a 
picture. This unfortunately happened to me when I was testing both boards.

The great part of this design, is that it allows you to add any accelerator 
or memory expansion card that goes over the CPU but it also makes for a 
fragile design. The flex cables are very thin and the connectors between the 
Denise adapter and HDMI can be easily broken. I suggest using a magnifying 
glass or if you wear glasses take them off to have a close look. Use as 
little force as possible, the travel of the locking mechanism is very short
and moves suddenly when lose.

Otherwise the PBNV3 is a very tidy solution to getting video out of your
Amiga and comes with the bonus of 1Mb chip ram, extra clockports and a RTC
socket.

@{b}Standard Adapter@{ub}

This seems to be the most common and earliest variant of the RGB2HDMI, 
rectangle in shape the Pi sits a top the card at a horizontal angle to
the Denise. There are other versions where it has been turned vertically
but I have not been able to obtain that version yet. Compared to the 
PiggyBackNotV3, this is much simpler to install but it also puts a bit
more pressure onto the Denise. I also found the connection to be quite
squishy, any small amount of pressure and the board would pop off. I had
tried to use the male mini HDMI to female HDMI adapter that was sent by
Amigastore.ey and the part that plugs into the Pi was pushing on my low 
profile CF adapter, this caused the adapter to pop off any time I moved 
the Amiga or plugged in the HDMI cable. Not an ideal situation at all.

There is a solution to this though, if you have already removed your RF
modulator you can install a female HDMI port that will connected with a
flex cable. Due to the angle of the standard HDMI2RGB board you need to
find a male mini HDMI cable that is straight, and not the angled one. 
However I believe the angled type will work on the PBNV3 though. Once
again you need to be careful with the Denise connector, like the PBNV3
the connector will wear out after one or two times of attaching to the
Dense chip, it is really a one way trip whe putting on the board so 
make sure you have planned all your cabling in advance.

@{b}Picture Quality@{ub}

Compared to my Indivision ECS the RGB2HDMI does an incredible job, the
picture looks as if it is coming from an emulator. I have not seen a
real Amiga 600 output such a bright and crisp image before. To give you an
idea, when I used the Indivision, I could still see artifacts and waving
on the picture. With the RGB2HDMI the picture solid and smooth. 

It seems the card does not support the more exotic resolutions though
which the Indvision cards do but if you are happy to just run in the default 
PAl HiRes or HiRes Laced then this card cannot be beat in quality and price. 

Changing settings is a breeze with the button, one short press to move 
through the menus and one long press to select. There are many settings, 
from turning on and off scanlines, setting it for a different system, herz 
settings etc. There seems to be a lot to what is possible with the RGB2HDMI.

Installation of the firmware is a simple download from the RGB2HDMI website
and then use the RaspberryPiSDCardInstaller to set up the card.

@{b}Final Thoughts@{ub}

The RGB2HDMI is one of the best upgrades you can get for your A600, it makes
using the system so much nicer. I would like to have seen a more sturdy 
build regarding the Denise adapters, this is something the manufacters could
learn from the Indivision cards. Aside from this issue the cards are very 
nicely made and it is great there are a variety of types available for those 
who have fastram/accelerator and those who want to keep their Amigas stock 
but still use a modern display.

@endnode

@node furiareview "Hardware review: Furia Amiga 600 Accelerator"
@toc reviews
============================================================================
@{b}Hardware Review: Furia Amiga 600 Accelerator@{ub} - by @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

@{b}Product Name@{ub}
Furia A600 Accelerator PCB rev.3 Firmware v13.1

@{b}Developed By@{ub}
Boris Krizma

@{b}Available From@{ub}
amiga-shop.net
amigstore.eu
retropassion.co.uk
lotharek.pl
       
@{b}Price@{ub}
130 EUR
  
@{b}Hardware/Software Requirements@{ub}
Amiga 600

@{b}Test Machine@{ub}
Amiga 600/3.1

@{b}Review@{ub}

@{i}A Bit of a Reputation@{ui}

It was a with a bit of trepidation that I put the Furia into the shopping
cart and paid. If you are on any of the Amiga boards you will have seen
the numerous threads asking for help with the Furia. It seems to be a 
magical beast who grants it{s power to only those few it deems are worthy
of it. On paper the card looks very nice:

* 680EC020 at 33Mhz
* MC68882 FPU at 40Mhz
* 9.5Mb of RAM
* PCMCIA friendly
* Maprom ability

A very robust set of features that will make your Amiga 600 sing and fly
while doing tasks. The version that I received was the lastest revision
with a black board instead of the red and white versions. As a precaution
I also bought a *compatible* CF and SD card from Amigastore.eu, they came
preinstalled with Workbench.

@{b}The Board Itself@{ub}

The board is pretty large and covers a large portion of the motherboard, if
you have an RGB2HDMI then you will need the versions that have the flex 
cable or the PiggyBackNotV3. There is a massive heatsink that covers most 
of the board with a jumper near the bottom to control the speed of the IDE
interface. It clicks on with a very nice click, and if you want to (but I
do not recommend doing so) you can lift the Amiga with Furia attached.
This is something that the RGB2HDMI manufacturers could learn, the adapters
need to clip on properly otherwise it is just a waste of Amiga users money.

Once the board was snuggly and the *compatible* CF installed, it was time 
to turn on the Amiga and see if the trouble past was behind the Furia. On
first power the Amiga just sat with a black screen, remembering from forums
that the board needed to have some considerable pressure added when 
installing, I turned everything off and applied some more pressure to the
card. Once again I turned on the Amiga and low and behold it booted to 
Workbench, and wow what a fast boot at that. I opened some windows to see
how it felt and the Amiga 600 just flew, opening drawers and rendering 
windows like never before. Just from the Workbench experience this little
card chugging along.

However I was still a bit wary and decided to try some more intensive hard
disk work copying some files over and this is where the Furia fell over.
As soon as I started to copy some files from one partition to another the
Amiga froze, only a three finger salute allowed me to get the Amiga back
again. Hmm so it seems there is still an issue with CF flash cards, no 
worries I have a fast SanDisk SD card, so in went the CF card adapter and
SD card. Again the Amiga did not boot on a cold start, when it did reboot
it got about half way into the boot sequence and then just hung. This was
not looking promising.

After a few hours of work I could get the Amiga to only boot with the CF
card from Amigastore.eu, but even then doing any hard disk work would lock
up the Amiga. After a few days of trying various other tricks such as 
changing the file system to a new one and other types of installs of 
Workbench the Amiga and Furia were not stable together. I decided to send
the card back to Amigastore.eu, they had a look and found the card to not
be working correctly at their end as well. So from the looks of it this
was an unlucky card.

@{b}Final Thoughts@{ub}

When the card was in use my Amiga 600 was just speeding through everything
it was a great joy to use. It is amazing how much power the card provides
to the lowly A600. Though it is a pain to set up and I would hesitate
recommending this card to someone who is not experienced with the Amiga
or is willing to put in the hours and maybe days to get it working. If you
are able to get it working then you will have one hell of a fast Amiga but
there is no guarantee that it will work at all in your system.

A card with much potential hamstrung by a fiddly setup and random 
compatibilty with CF and SD cards. If you can master the Furia then it is
a great card, but that is if you CAN master it.

@endnode

@node drawergeniereview "Software Review: DrawerGenie"
@toc reviews
============================================================================
@{b}Software Review: DrawerGenie@{ub} - by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================ 

@{b}Product Name@{ub}
DrawerGenie

@{b}Developed By@{ub}
Rob Cranley

@{b}Available From@{ub}
aminet.net/packages/util/wb/DrawerGenie
       
@{b}Price@{ub}
Free
  
@{b}Hardware/Software Requirements@{ub}
Workbench 3.1.4+

@{b}Test Machine@{ub}
Amiga 1200/3.2/TF1260

@{b}Review@{ub}

Since OS3.2 cameout there has been a slow trickle of OS3.2 targetted 
programs. Even though it is less than I would like to see what has been
comeout are stellar releases. One such programme is DrawerGenie. It is 
freely available from Aminet and is well worth a look, let's delve into its 
features.

In a nutshell DrawerGenie takes much of the functionally usually accessed
from the menu and puts them within easy reach via a button bar displayed
in the window. However it is not limited to the standard functions available
from the menu, there is much more power in this little tool. The toolbar is
brought up by pressing F1, according to the author he has not had the time
to implement the tool bar showing automatically, however pressing F1 to 
bring up the toolbar is a fast and efficient way. It keeps the tool out of
the way when not needed. So what is offered when you press F1, a list of
actions is listed below:

	* Back
	* Parent
	* Cut
	* Copy
	* Paste
	* Refresh
	* New Drawer
	* Icon Information
	* Delete
	* View Type
	* Sort
	* File Visibility
	* Rename
	* Source
	* Destination
	* Copy To
	* Move To
	* View Files    
	* Select All
	* New Shell
	* Unpack Archive
	* View Archive
	* Pack Archive
	* Find Files	
                    
As you can see the available actions is very extensive and as such you will
need to be running Workbench in a relatively high resolution, at least a 
Laced mod. HiRes PAL makes for a bit of a tight squeeze, I found that with
HIGHGFX: Super-HighRes the bar fit very nicely into the windows. 

@{b}In Use@{ub}

As stated before to get access to the button bar you need to press F1, this
also applies when you open a new window, the bar will not be carried across
to a new window. The functions I found to be very useful and quickly 
DrawerGenie became part of my usual Workbench flow, I find that when I do
not have it installed I am looking for it. Just the simple task of press
a button to refresh the window to find contents is a much faster experience
that having to go to the drop down menu. My system runs at 50Mhz with the
060, I have a Rev 5 so I unable to run the system any faster. But 
DrawerGenie really flies on my system, it also works well with CaBoom the
utility for animating the opening and closing of windows which sometimes
causes conflicts with other commodities.

Many of the tasks that I would usually go to DOPUS for are not taken care
of quickly with DrawerGenie such as unpacking/packing a file or viewing an
archive's contents.

@{b}Final Thoughts@{ub}

This review has only touched the surface of what DrawerGenie is capable of
but in the short time that I have used it, DrawerGenie has become an 
essential tool that has earned a permanent place in my WBStartUp drawer. If
you have an OS3.1.4  or higher system then you owe it to yourself to give
this tool a try. If you want to learn more about DrawerGenie then please
read the @{"interview" link robcranley} we have with the developer in this issue.
                        
@endnode

