============================================================================
@{b}Weasels Gaming Corner: Something old and something new@{ub} - by @{"Ivan Sorensen" link ivansorensen}
============================================================================

The Weasels Gaming Corner

This issue I again wanted to take a look at two titles, one new (to the 
Amiga) and one from back in the day.

First up we have Metal Law: A side scrolling @{b}run and gun@{ub} with more 
than a little bit of Judge Dredd vibes about it. The game has pretty catchy 
music and surprisingly large sprites. It also features some interesting 
movement capabilities and pretty good visuals. 

The gameplay is fairly straight forward: Move around the level, collect a 
few items and blow away anything that moves. Along the way you have access 
to a rocket assisted double jump feature, something not commonly seen in 
Amiga platformers. 

There is a particular vibe I always associate with the Amiga: Games that 
are perhaps a bit more ambitious than what the developers could pull off 
and Metal Law feels like it fits in that category. It never quite reaches 
what I think the developers hoped it would, but it makes for a fun evening 
of blasting mutant scum in the sewers.

Metal Law is not especially long or difficult so it is a game you stand a 
fair chance of being able to complete with a bit of work.

A WHDLoad version is available requiring 1 MB of RAM. The game does not 
require AGA. 

On a more modern note we have an Amiga port of Magica. Originally an 
Amstrad game, this can be downloaded from Andy Noble's website at:

=> http://andynoble.co.uk/ 

A WHDLoad install is also available adding a number of trainer options. 

Magica is a platformer where you have to zap various fantasy creatures, 
then run to touch them before they wake up again. If you do, they are flung 
across the platform (stunning any creatures they hit) and turn into a potion. 
Your goal is to turn every creature on the screen into a potion, collect 
them all and then reach the exit when it appears, usually against a 50 
second time limit.
 
The game is very reminiscent of other single screen games like Bubble Bobble 
but manages to have its own identity. The music is fantastic and the 
graphics and animation is quite pleasing while being simple.
 
The game saves your progress so you can knock out a few levels and come back 
to it later. 

Well recommended. 

Lastly I wanted to talk about a peculiar phenomena: Being captivated by a 
bad game. The game in question is Death Mask: An attempt to cash in on the 
rise of Doom clones with a @{b}step by step 90 degree turns@{ub} gameplay 
approach (similar to Hired Guns but without any of the complexity of that 
game). 

Death Mask is pretty weak in all regards: The sound is pretty limited, the 
graphics engine has some weird effects where you can often see through doors 
when turning, the controls manage to both be stiff AND over responsive at 
the same time and combat is completely banal (You can only shoot straight 
ahead). Enemy AI is non existent and most have only a couple frames of 
animation (and a few do not appear to be animated at all). There are a few 
saving graces like a map that indicates objectives and enemies on it, as 
well as the ability to play two player split screen. We played this back in 
the day since it could be played two player on even an A500 and I 
occasionally replay it just to relive a few memories. It is by all accounts 
a pretty bad game and yet I've gotten the burning urge to actually play it 
to completion. 

Does this ever happen to you? 

When you sit down this weekend to do some Amiga gaming consider revisiting 
one of the games that you secretly knows was pretty bad and try to give it 
an honest shot at progressing. You may be surprised or maybe you won't. 

Weasel Out. 

@endnode

@node spheroidreview
@toc gamereviews
============================================================================
@{b}Game Review: Spheroid@{ub} - by @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

@{b}Product Name@{ub}
Spheroid (Demo)
@{b}Developed By@{ub}
Andrew Vaisey
@{b}Available From@{ub}
https://arkanixlabs.itch.io/spheroid
@{b}Price@{ub}
Free
@{b}Hardware/Software Requirements@{ub}
OCS+ IMB Ram
@{b}Test Machine@{ub}
Amiga 1200/TF1 260/OS 3.2. 2/ Indivision AGA Mk3

@{b}Review@{ub}

It is very rare for my wife to come running into the study when I am
playing a game, however, she heard me muttering various colour names,
"red and grey, red and grey', over and over. She was under the impression
that I was having some kind of mental breakdown. Instead, she found me
sitting in front of my Amiga, controller in hand, deep in concentration
moving a small sphere around a screen of coloured tiles. With the hour
past my wife was sitting in the same position, glued to the screen repeating
colour names over and over. And so this is how we were both introduced to
the game Spheroid.

Spheroid at its core is a simple move of the sphere around using the
various tiles. There are several coloured tiles and others that allow you
to transport from one area to another, ones that collapse after you roll
over them, others are iced sending your sphere careening off the screen
into the black abyss. Where things get more complicated are the "safe"
colours, it may be two or more, depending on the screen. If you roll
over another colour you explode in an exuberant way with the explosion
effect sounding very much like from the A-Team.

That is all there is really to it, roll your ball around the screen and
figure out the path to the exit. However, while it sounds simple, the game
gets fiendishly difficult quickly as the screens get more complicated with
routes that seem simple at first glance but are much more complex than at
first glance. Add in the time limit that only starts counting down when
you stop moving and you will find yourself repeating colours and
sweating while moving your little sphere around the screen.
The graphics are nicely drawn, with the title screen giving you all the
information you need, so study it first before entering the game. It has a
very early 90s feel, while the graphics are simple during gameplay they
are pleasant to look at and provide you with the visual cues you need to
complete the level.

For audio, we are treated to a stomping acid house track, something that I
would not normally be associated with a puzzle game but it works very well,
getting your heart pumping and adding to the sense of pressure and time.

@{b}Final Thoughts@{ub}

Spheroid is one of the most enjoyable games I have played in a long time.
The gameplay is simple and straightforward but with puzzles that can get 
quite challenging, well for me at least. It has that essential element of 
seeming easier than it is and hooking you in with one more try. It is much 
fun to play as my wife can attest to, it is a game that will have you 
thinking about the puzzles hours after you have finished playing it. On top 
of that, the game looks very polished with simple but effective graphics 
and a pumping soundtrack.

On a side note, I teach students with learning difficulties such as dyslexia 
and ADHD. During my time reviewing Spheroid, I tested it on a few of my 
students and noted some interesting things.
 
a) Even though it was a retro looking game they quickly got into it and
   enjoyed it greatly.
b) The most surprising was how it helped  with their concentration. After 
   playing they were able to concentrate better in the lesson and do
   more work. 

It is known gaming can help but I have never seen it before as with 
Spheroid.

@{b}Pros and Cons:@{ub}
+ Simple but nice to look at graphics
+ Music is pumping and suits the game well
+ Gameplay is simple but hides a very deep game
  I cannot think of anything negative, other than maybe some variety in the 
  music

@{b}Scores@{ub}
Gameplay: 10/10
Graphics: 8/10
Sound:    8/10
Overall:  8.6/10

A very addictive and smart game that will have you hooked for hours if not 
days.

@endnode

@node tenebra12review 
@toc gamereviews
============================================================================
@{b}Game Review: Tenebra 1 and 2@{ub} - by @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

@{b}Product Name@{ub}
Tenebra 1 and 2
@{b}Developed By@{ub}
Ali Pouladi
@{b}Available From@{ub}
https://h4plo.itch.io/tenebra
@{b}Price@{ub}
Free/Donation
@{b}Hardware/Software Requirements@{ub}
OCS+ 1.3+ 512KB Ram
@{b}Test Machine@{ub}
Amiga 1200/TF1 260/OS 3.2. 2/ Indivision AGA Mk3
Amiga 600/3.1/xT 020

@{b}Review@{ub}

By now you probably have already heard of or seen details on these two games
having won game of the year in 2022 for Planeta Sinclair Awards, Tenebra has
been ported to pretty much every platform out there. For those who do not 
know about the game, it is a simple puzzle game with the aim being to find
the exit. This is achieved by moving lights, finding keys, lighting cold
braziers, increasing the range of your light with oil, squeezing through
cracks, fixing broken rails with a hammer, activating light sensitive 
sensors and passing through archways that collapse after you. Tenebra 1
contains 31 levels and Tenebra 2 has 35. The Amiga version can also be
run in HiRes Laced though you will need a flicker fixer to not get a 
headache.

The graphics are wonderfully simple, using only two colours but managed to 
be very effective. The light effect is achived by simple white dots but it
works very well. When you finished a level it is revealed completely and I
am always surprised by how simple the level is. It is a very interesting
example of how our brain copes with a lack of information. When I am moving
around the gameplay area I feel as if the room is much bigger and 
complicated. In a way it is almost like reading a book since you have to
create much of the scenario in your head, something that is perhaps missing
in modern games. There is also the option to have the screen flicker to
mimic the effect of a torch, it nice that the feature can be turned off.

Audio wise there is not much except for a haunting wind in the background 
and the sound effects for doors, switcheds and keys. Again minimalistic
but highly effective with the option to be turned off.

Gameplay is very simple but gradually becomes more complicated, it is 
important to not rush head on into the game and read the hints at the
beginning of each stage. The puzzles are not particulary hard but they
did cause to think for a while. Control is done by the joystick, sadly
there is no keyboard control which I think would suit this type of game
more than using a joystick/control pad. Fingers crossed this will be
added in the future. It is also nice to have the level codes so that 
you can go back to the game at a later date.

I greatly enjoyed playing both games, however if you have not played the
first one then it is not advisable to go straight to Tenebra 2 as the first
one teaches you much of the basics and will help when playing the second
game.
 
@{b}Final Thoughts@{ub}

Tenebra 1 and 2 are wonderfully addictive and fun to play, they are easy to 
pick up and not too difficult. While some might balk at the simple graphics
they work more the game's advantage. I also played the Mac version but 
found the game lost some of its charm with the high resolution graphics and
light effects. Tenebra takes me back to playing games on our ZX81 and D&D
or HeroQuest with my mates. Download the game this winter and play it with
a family member if possible as it works great as a team game. While the
game is free I recommend paying the developer whatever you can as way of 
thanks for their efforts.
 
@{b}Pros and Cons:@{ub}
+ Simple graphics
+ Background sound effect suits the game well
+ Gameplay is easy to pick up and not too hard
- No keyboard control, a game like this would really benefit from keyboard
  control

@{b}Scores@{ub}
Gameplay: 10/10
Graphics: 8/10
Sound:    8/10
Overall:  8.6/10

Fantastic game with lots of atmosphere, don't be put off by the graphics
as they help to create a better game.

@endnode


