@node a314time "A314-CP Fix: A314.device not found"
@toc guides
=============================================================================
@{b}A314-CP Fix: A314.device not found@{ub} - by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
=============================================================================

The A314-CP has grown to become one of my favourite add ons for the Amiga 
due to its ease of use and expansion possibilities. However there has been 
one issue that has been bugging me for a while. It arises from the Pi side 
of things due to the OS taking around 15 seconds to boot and then connect 
to the Internet. Since my Al200 has a TF1260 there is not extra clock port 
to have a battery RTC installed. So I need to grab the time and date from 
the Internet. This is done easily with the 'pisetclock' command in the 
start up sequence or using 'ntp' program to grab the time from an online 
server.

The issues arise due to the boot time of my Workbench being faster than the 
Pi OS, this then results in an error in loading the A314.device and the 
time not being set properly. After a quick think about the issue it was 
obvious that I needed to time the network connection and setclock command to 
when the Pi was ready and connected to the network. The solution came about 
with some help from Ivan from the Tokyo Retro Computer users meet.

What we need to do is put a delay into the Workbench, and where you put this 
delay is important. I am using Roadshow for my TCP/IP stack as such this 
command needs to be put before loading Roadshow. In my case Roadshow is 
loaded from the 'user-startup' file, so I need to add a delay to the boot 
sequence just before it loads Roadshow, to give time for the PiOS to connect 
to the internet. A simple command of 'WAIT 30 SEC' is all that is needed. I 
tested it with a shorter time and for my setup, 30 seconds gave me the best 
results, it could vary depending on your setup. A part of my user-startup 
is shown below ..

WAIT 30 SEC
;BEGIN Roadshow
If EXISTS S:Network-Startup Execute S:Network-Startup Endlf
;END Roadshow

This will stop the error of A314.device not being loaded or unavailable.
Now that issue is sorted we can load the 'pisetclock' command, I found the 
most reliable place to put it was in the 'startup-sequence' right after the 
'LoadWB' command, as can be seen below ...


C:LoadWB C:PiSetClock EndCLI >NIL:

I tried placing it earlier before 'LoadWB' but it was not so reliable when 
setting the clock. Having it just after 'LoadWB' sets the clock about 5 
seconds after Workbench has loaded, giving you the feel of having a RTC 
inside your Amiga. This is a very simple solution and though you do have to 
wait a bit longer for the Amiga to boot it gives you a stable clock and date 
solution. The other alternatives would be to buy a clock port expander and 
add a RTC card to the board along with the A314-CP. But if you are happy 
with the 30 second delay then this is a great option, you might be even able 
to shave a few seconds off the time depending on your setup.

@endnode

@node creativegraphics "Creative Graphics: 3D Objects and A Word Processor"
@toc guides
=============================================================================
@{b}Creative Graphics: 3D Objects and A Word Processor@{ub} - by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
=============================================================================

Words create worlds, each time we pick up a book and start reading we are 
creating a fully fleshed world in our mind just from the words of the 
pages. But what about creating 3D objects that can be rendered in any 3D 
rendering software with your word processor?

Welcome to Creative Graphics, a new series that will look at creative ways 
of making graphics without adhering to any particular software. Instead of 
making you into a professional pixel artist, this series will explore how 
to use the Amiga and the variety of software in fun and creative ways. To 
use a well-known phrase, "Standing on the shoulders of giants", the first 
article in this series will take influence from an article in the US 
magazine Amazing Computing.

The first time I read the article the thing that caught my attention most 
was when it mentioned using a word processor to create a 3D object. My 
curiosity peaked, I read the article and followed the guides and greatly 
enjoyed it. So to begin this series we will borrow some ideas and go a bit 
beyond. To begin with we will need the following software:

	* Final Writer 5 (Or other word processors that can create tables)
	* ImageFX 2+
	* Pixel 3D Pro (This can be found on Amiga Format disk AF65A)
	* LightWave 3D (Or any other 3D rendering software)

To begin with let's open up FinalWriter, and using the menu bar go to
'Tables' and select 'Create'. Under the 'Settings' tab set columns to
10 and rows to 5, 'Column Width' should be 0.75 inches. Select the 'Lines'
tab and set everything that has a weight of 1 point to 4 points. Select
'Use' and generate the table. You might need to drag the table so it is
centred on the page. Keeping FinalWriter open, find ImageFX and start it 
up. Click the 'Buffer' button and select 'Grab Screen', you should see one 
that says "Final Writer - R", choose it and you will see a screen capture 
of FinalWriter show up on the ImageFX screen. You will need to crop the 
image so only the table is showing and this is easily done in ImageFX by 
clicking on 'Size', then 'Crop'. A box with handles will appear over your 
image, you can then drag them to fit the table. If you need to move the 
restraining box then click inside and drag. Just click on 'Crop' and you 
will see your cropped image appear if you need to crop more off repeat the 
process.

Next, we will need to reduce the colour of the image from whatever it was 
down to 2 colours. The reason is that Pixel 3D Pro only works with 2 colour 
images. Once you have rendered the image down to 2 colours, you will need 
to reverse the black-and-white image. This can be done by clicking on 
'Color' when in Toolbox (Selected from the right side) and then 'Negative'. 
Render the image as 2 colours again and save the image as 'Rendered Image' 
not '24-Bit Buffer'. Now you can close FinalWriter and ImageFX.

@{b}Pixel 3D Pro@{ub}

In the original article, it had called for the use of Pixel 3D Pro version
2, however, it is very hard to find a working copy of the programme. So as 
an alternative, you can download the previous version that came free with 
Amiga Format on cover disk AF65A.
 
Load up Pixel 3D Pro and you are presented with a display that looks similar 
to VistaPro. Find and click on the 'Load' hillton, locate your image and 
click on 'Accept'. A 2D image of your table will appear, to make it 3D, all 
we need to do is choose 'Extrude' from the left side. A requester will pop 
up and the only detail you need to change is the 'Extrude Value' to 30, then 
click on 'OK'. Now you will be presented with a wireframe representation of 
your table which you can move freely around. However we are not quite 
finished yet, we need to save the object by clicking on 'Save' and 
selecting the 3D program you will use to render the object. In my case I 
chose 'LightWave 3D', once it is saved you can close down Pixel 3D Pro and 
get ready for LighWave 3D, Imagine, Aladdin or whatever is your weapon of 
choice.

@{b}Landscapes and Tables@{ub}

Now you have your 3D object that started as a table in FinalWriter, pretty 
neat, right? 

From here you can use the object any way you like, create a city landscape 
where you can fly through the windows of skyscrapers, create a massive 
bookshelf, or maybe add a flat object to act like glass against the table 
object. By loading in many of the table objects and applying surfaces to 
them you can create unique landscapes where the light filters through the 
spaces in the tables. Why did we do it this way? Aside from being a fun 
experiment, it is also a much faster way to create an object like a 3D 
table this way, rather than having to cut and paste various objects 
together in the LightWave 3D modeller.

If you find this article enjoyable and give it a try, we would love to see 
your work. Please submit your creations to the WhatIFF? forum at:

=> https://forum.whatiff.info

Look for 'Readers Submissions' and find the appropriate category to submit 
your work.

@endnode

@node brilliance101 "Brilliance 101 - Tokyo Bay"
@toc guides
=============================================================================
@{b}Brilliance 101 Part 11@{ub} - by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
=============================================================================

By now the due date for the Amiga Art Competition has passed and so I
thought it might be worth going over my entry and how I created it. As per
usual I used Brilliance as while I started and really like DPaint,
Brilliance is more refined art package that is aimed at the artiste
So on to my image, first off the inspiration for my picture came about when
I was travelling Tokyo on the train. From my staâ¬ion the train line goes
over Tokyo bay and I get a great view of the bay and far into the distance e
It was on one trip and the sky was bright blue with huge white clouds on the
horizon and the water splattered with the sun's reflections. It struck me
as being quite beautiful. So I did what any typical Amiga user would do,
pulled out my laptop, started up UAE for Mac and sketched an outline of the
view in Brilliance. From there I had to stop as drawing with the mouse pad
was more stress than I wanted.

The initial sketch had the bottom part of the image in blue for the bay
and then I sketched the cloud shapes roughly. On another buffer I had
created the building silhouettes so that I could paste them in once I
was on my real Amiga.

Well, here I am now at my A1 200 and time to import the image from my laptop
thanks to the A 314-CP card it was a simple case of e-mailing it to my A1200
and the loading it into Brilliance. The first part of the image I worked on
was the water. I chose a simple gradient going from a darker blue to a
light blue with dithering enabled to give it a rougher look. However the
water looked a bit sterile and I wanted to include the reflections on the
water. This was achieved by drawing a small wave line in white with a pen
tip of about 3 pixels. I then made a brush out of the wave and pasted it on
the water. I held down the 'Left Shift' key to keep the cursor on the same
horizontal line when getting near the horizon. Once I had pasted down
several waves, I then used to the Transparent' tool to paste the brush on
the water and over some of the other waves to create more depth and variety
to the waves. Finally to create the impression of water the Smear' tool
was used on all the waves to make it look like the wave is moving. I find
the Smear' tool very useful when I want to create a more natural looking
image, especially as I am not artistically skilled.

Next it was time to move onto the clouds, I had to think hard on this one
and recalled that the clouds were darker at the bottom and lighter at the
top. The ' Gradient' tool came in very handy again. Choosing a colour that
is almost white and a very slightly dark grey I had my gradient, however
I did not want to use a standard verticle gradient. The gradient would
need to follow the contours of the clouds and I found the best was was to
use 'Highlight' gradient with the first colour, i.e. grey starting at the
bottom. So when the red line appeared after clicking the 'Fill' tool I
dragged it to the bottom on the cloud and it filled out nicely around
the edges. Now I shoud mention here that there are several layers of
clouds so make sure to have each of your cloud layers filled in a
completely different colour, it can be pink, red, purple etc. so that you
do not have a leaky flood as what happened to Andy Warhol ;)

Going back to the spare buffer I could now paste in the buildings on the
horizonal using various levels of shading, One of the easiest buildings to
see from the train is Tokyo Sky Tree, it has a very distinctive shape which
translates nicely into silhouette form.

So now we are finished with the basic scene of Tokyo bay, however I wanted
to create an image of the view from inside the train. To help save memory I
created a new separate image for the internal view. This is where my
limited art skills really started to let me down. My plan to was to create
a window with the a 3D effect and place sillhouettes of the passengers in
front of me. We will look at how this effect was achieved in the next issue.


@endnode

@node imagefx101 "ImageFX 101 Basics - Part 2"
@toc guides
============================================================================
@{b}ImageFX 101 Basics - Part 2@{ub} - by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

I hope you enjoyed the first part of our journey into ImageFX, it is a very
powerful program that is bit hamstrung by a rather difficult GUI. In this
part of the series we will look at a feature only found in version 4.5 of
ImageFX, that is the layer feauture. Something that has been the prevail of
Photoshop it has finally come to ImageFX, though it is not the only program
to have layers on the Amiga, Photogenics also has that feauture.
As with almost everything in ImageFX you need to start with the buffers,
for this guide you will need to load the standard version of ImageFX as
the Classic version does not seem to support layers as well. For this
example we will be using the included images with the ImageFX install. To
start open the file (SmallGal.JPG), once the image loaded we want to load
another image, the best way to do this is too click on 'Buffer' locate
' Load New' and choose the (SmallGuy.JPG) Now you should have two images
loaded in separate windows. Go back to the main window and look for the RGB
buttons, on the left of them you will find the Layers button. First make
sure which image you want as your main image, this is done by click on the
image itsefl. Then click on the Layers button and locate the gadget at the
top right and press it. A menu will pop up, choose 'New Layer From Buffer
and choose (SmallGuy.JPG). You will see the picture of (SmallGuy.JPG) cover
up the original image, you can hide it from view by clicking on the eye
icon in the Layer Manager.

From here you can have a play with the 'Mode' which has some interesting
effects. Choose 'Maximum' and 'Minimum' for some startling and rather
scary effects. Double clicking on the layer will bring up more options
for that particular layer. The layers can be moved by using the
Layer Manager, select your layer and use the pop up menu to move the
layer upper or lower. This should get you started with the basics of using
layers, next issue we will look at Photogenics and see how it compares to
ImageFX.

On another note, the first ImageFX tutorial has had some great feedback from
readers, some have even written in with suggestions. Once came from Boris,
who has another way to create a brush in ImageFX. I will hand it over to
Boris from here:

@{i}I don't know if it is easier, but it is more exact without loosing parts of
your image.

When the image is rotated, the background around the image has one color
In my case it is black. You choose now not the Poi y-tool for cutting, but
the Flood-option. Then you pick with this the black area. After this you
look in the Buffer-window for the Region-button. In the next window you
choose "Invert Region", then Okay. Now you choose the button "Pickup Region"
in the Brush-window ... et voila: you have the single rotated picture as
brush. I LOVE ImageFX!@{ui}

Thank you Boris for your suggestion, if anyone else has some ideas,
corrections or wishes to write their own guide then contact us on the forum
or via e-mail at: submissions@whatiff. info

@endnode  

@node df1todf0 "Make DF1 work just like DF0"
@toc guides
============================================================================
@{b}How to make your external DF1 work just like DF0@{ub} - by: @{"John Scolieri" link johnscolieri}
============================================================================
How to make your external DF1 work just like DF0 with the PiStorm32 
accelerator.

So maybe you're like me at the moment and don't have an internal floppy 
drive handy to use in your Amiga 1200 with a PiStorm32 accelerator and Emu68 
but you do have an external floppy drive. And if you're like me then 
sometimes you want to boot up 'real' disks straight from boot up without 
entering Workbench and that won't work 'most' times unless your booting 
from DFO.

Luckily for us it's very simple to switch DF1 to DF0 when running Emu68 
which is as follows:

1- Take the microSD card out of your PiStorm32 and connect it to your PC.

2- In the main FAT32 partition there is a file called 'cmdline.txt'. If it 
   doesn't exist just create a new .txt file and name it cmdline.txt.

3- Open cmdline.text and add 'swap_df0_with_df1' (no quotes and it must be 
   on one single line)

4- Save the file and reinsert microSD card into your PiStorm32.

After you boot up again to Workbench you'll see you're external drive now 
as DF0 !

@endnode
      		   
@node articles "Articles"
@toc contents
============================================================================
@{b}-=  A R T I C L E S =-------------------------------------------------------@{ub}
