============================================================================
@{b}The Amiga Philosopher's stance on Amiga Games@{ub} - by: @{"Ivan Sorensen" link ivansorensen}
============================================================================

I find that while there is a lot of talk about Amiga gaming on the internet, 
whether on Youtube or the various forums and social media sites, there are 
certain types of posts that always seem to come up:

The game is bad because it had too much disk swapping / could not be 
installed on a hard drive / the Super Nintendo version was better / it was 
ported from the Atari / it was not arcade perfect and so forth.

Often the comments seem to be made by people who admit they do not play 
Amiga games any longer or have not touched the particular game since 1989.

These opinions often tend to cement themselves as people repeat opinions 
they have read, when they are not themselves familiar with the game in 
question. So soon @{b}everybody knows xxx is bad because yyy@{ub} which both 
gives a distorted perception of how games were received at the time but also 
keeps people away from games that they might in fact end up enjoying quite 
a bit if they tried them. 

So I would like to present an alternate view of games on the Amiga that is 
rooted in a different approach. The following points are not in order of 
importance and their individual applicability may vary depending on the game 
in question. Take it as a starting point or a set of guidelines and make up 
your own mind.

@{b}Point 1:@{ub}
To me it never matters if the Amiga version is the optimal port of the game 
or what other platforms it appeared on.

If I am sitting down to play an Amiga game, I am interested in the game on 
the Amiga, not a hypothetical better version on a different system.

This is particularly important if you are trying to better understand the 
historical side of the Amiga gaming scene. Games like Street Fighter 2 were 
greeted pretty enthusiastically in magazines at the time, even though they 
are considered to be bad ports today.

This also goes for games that were @{b}ST ports@{ub}: Nobody I knew had an 
ST so it did not make any difference to us at the time and it still does 
not. If the choice is between a fun game in 16 colours and a boring game in 
32 colours, surely we all agree that the fun game is the better outcome? 

@{b}Point 2:@{ub}
My opinion of a game is based on the machine I can play it on. 

That may sound selfish but let me explain: Amiga owners I think often suffer 
a peculiar psychological effect where we spend hundreds (or thousands) of 
dollars tricking out machines but every game must run flawlessly on an 
unexpanded Amiga 500. I don't understand it.
 
My system has a pretty fast 68030 which I wager is in the middle of the 
Amiga scene these days: You get people with unexpanded or barely expanded 
systems and you get people with monster fast systems but the median system 
is probably not that far from what I am using. 

So my stance on a game is based on how it performs on that system. It 
doesn't really matter if Fears for example runs poorly on a stock A1200 
because who is going to try to play it on that system in 2023?

This goes especially so for hard drives. People will complain about Beneath 
a Steel Sky coming on a huge stack of floppies but the game is hard drive 
installable. Is any serious Amiga fan really going to play the game running 
off floppies? 

This has given rise to a strange attitude among Amiga fans where people 
forget that while many games were not HD installable, plenty of them were 
(and most of the games that came on tons of disks like RPGs and adventure 
games supported hard drives).

There was nothing stopping you from installing Civilization or UFO to a 
hard drive in 1992 but people will still complain about disk swapping in 
UFO in 2023. 

Back in the day some magazines begin noting if a game ran better or had 
more features on an A1200 or on an expanded machine and I think that is 
something that modern reviewers should take into account. There is no reason 
to be perpetually mired in 1985 (even if we are nostalgic retro-nerds).

@{b}Point 3:@{ub}
My opinion is based on the version that exists today.

This ties into point 2 to an extent but unless you are strictly looking at 
the game in its historical context, there is no reason to not use the most 
updated version which usually means WHDLoad. Whether its preloading, adding 
trainers or expanding the control options, a lot of games are greatly 
improved by using this version.

Frustrated that you can't use a button to jump? Many games now do support 
that! 

Is there any reason to play the worse version? Again, if you are after the 
strict historical experience sure, I get it but otherwise get the better 
one. 

This is not even that ahistorical. I had games where I would use the cracked 
version over the disks I had purchased, because the cracked version added a 
trainer or level jump option or something similar.
 
Likewise some games did receive updated files or patches. That was harder to 
come by in those days but with Aminet it started to become a thing and PD 
games often had multiple versions released with improvements and bug fixes.

@{b}In conclusion:@{ub}
When I get back to reviewing games online, the games will be based on the 
most updated WHDLoad version running on my modestly expanded 1200 and based 
strictly on the Amiga version of the game.

  
@endnode

@node whatcommodoredidright
@toc articles
============================================================================
@{b}Things Commodore Did Right@{ub} - by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

What comes to mind when you think about US Commodore Amiga advertising?
Maybe the fetus on a stick, an Amiga 1 000 on a pedestal, an old man? When
it comes to the best advertising of the Amiga, the UK can arguably be
seen as a leader, yes it was video game focused but it did put the Amiga
in a good light. Well let me take you back to 1 988/89 when Commodore US
surprised many in the United States with a series of ground breaking and
fun TV advertisements. In these ads you had an American politician, Apollo
astronauts, famous musicians of the time and sports celebrities all
together.

I was fortunate enough to be living in the States when I got my first
Amiga. We had just moved to Pennsylvania and needed a computer to replace
our aging ZX Spectrum. After seeing the A500 in the stores we were quickly
convinced this was the computer for us. It was also during this time that
I would witness some of the best Commodore US advertising ever.
The first thing that comes to mind when I recall seeing the advertisements
was the music. They used The Goonies soundtrack and it greatly helped to
create a sense of excitement and wonder. For a generation that grew up
with Star Wars, Indiana Jones, The Goonies, Ghostbusters, E.T., The A-Team
and Airwolf these new advertisements spoke our language in tone and theme.

The standard setup of the advertisements were a normal looking middle class
American home, a teenage boy named Steve and his Amiga. Each advertisement
focused on one aspect of the Amiga's multimedia abilities. Video production
, music, and animation. In a stroke of genius they managed to convince stars
of the day to appear all together. Just to illustrate the celebrity royalty
that showed up, here is a list of all of them for just one of the ads.

	* Musicians: The Pointer Sisters, Burt Bacharach, Little Richard
	* NASA astronauts: Buzz Aldrin, Scott Carpenter, Gordon Cooper
	* US politician: Tip O 'Neill
	* Baseball player and coach: Tommy Lasorda

In just one ad they all appear asking for Stevie's help with their music,
building the ISS, calculations and more. Just think for a second of an ad
that would have that many celebrities showing their support for a Mac or
Windows PC today? It just does not seem possible.

A later episode had him tricking his nextdoor neighbour by hijacking their
TV and showing him accepting an award with the Amiga hooked up to a Genlock
and providing titles and effects.

This was really ground breaking because never before had a computer
advertisement show what computers and more importantly the Amiga was truly
capable of. It made using the Amiga look fun but also illustrated very well
how truly capable the the Amiga was. It is only recently we have had
advertisements showing what you can do with a smartphone but not with a
computer and certainly not in 1988.

If you think back to the ads that were shown in the UK the Amiga was mostly
marketed as a games machine but these ads from the US really showed how
versatile the Amiga was. It makes me wonder if they had been shown in the UK
how would it have impacted the general view of the Amiga. I hope this has
given you a better idea of how revolutionary the ads were and if you have
not seen them yet then pop on over to YouTube, I have included the links
below. It makes you wonder what could have been and more importantly enjoy
the excitement that the Amiga still generated back then.

Long ad with celebrities
=> https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=00z0U5DZhLc

Stevie tricking his next door neighbours
=> https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=96SJYB7wa0w

Stevie elevating his house
=> https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8R7xTR8j_2k

