@node amigald "Amiga Through the Lens of an LD Learner"
@toc articles 
============================================================================
@{b}Amiga Through the Lens of an LD Learner@{ub} - by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

LD, learning difficulty, commonly associated with dyslexia or ADHD, it
should not be confused with learning disability. In this article we are
going to concentrate on learning difficulty and how the Amiga can be used
as an aid in learning and concentration in ways that that modern hardware
and software cannot do offer.

From the start I think I should make clear that I am qualified dyslexia
specialist with over 10 years teaching experience of children with dyslexia
and ADHD. Over this time I have had the opportunity to experiment with
various teaching techniques, some failing and some working. One factor that
has been a common denominator is children love technology and they love old
technology as well I want to talk a bit about the teaching experience first 
to give some basis of how the Amiga can be helpful. 

For the majority of tutoring learners with dyslexia or ADHD, from now on we 
will use LD, patience and variety is a very important tool. When I say 
variety I mean using kinaesthetic methods, having the learner move their 
body, trace letters in the air, using sand to give a tactile feedback, 
speaking and writing at the same time. This is just the tip of some of the 
techniques applied. 

In some instances however writing by hand can become quite stressful and 
in these instances schools and tutors allow the student to use a computer to 
write on. Now it needs to be stated that using a smartphone or tablet is 
not advised, even one with an attached keyboard as the tactile feel from 
typing is an essential factor when writing with a computer. With the newer 
computers however there has been the fashion of making thinner keyboards 
with less travel and while this is making the keyboard/laptop thinner it 
is taking away a very useful tool in learning. When you have to push the 
keys harder, feel the shape of the key and hear the clickty clack of typing 
it all adds to helping create a stronger impression. You can probably try 
it yourself, try and touch type on a new thinner keyboard verses the ones 
with more travel, I think you will find your typing to be more accurate.

So this is one aspect of where the Amiga really helps, it provides a tactile
typing experience, where the learner can touch the keys, hear the sounds
and have to push a bit more than compared to a touch screen or newer type
keyboard.

We have now looked at how the Amiga provides a more tactile typing
experience which aids in the learning experience. Next we will look at how
using an Amiga word processor is better than any of the modern equivalents.
Any learner with LD with struggle to a greater or lesser extend with
concentration, as such, LD tutors will always look for ways to reduce the
amount of distractions. The smartphone is a gateway drug to distraction with
its notifications, multitasking, in coming phone calls and messages. The
modern computer is no less distracting with internet access easily available
and notifications becoming standard on a desktop computere With the Amiga
we can throw all of this away. I had a great experience when my student
first tried Excellence! he stopped and asked where the buttons were, how
can I draw, where is the browser?

He was on an Amiga 600 with just 2MB of ram.

While he found it jarring at first he quickly got drawn into the simple
GUI design, the low resolution graphics and tactile keyboard. There was
far less looking around, fiddling with buttons or swiping at the screen
just looking down at the keyboard to find his key and then looking at the
screen. I allowed him to do some simple editing such as adding bold or
using extra characters but it was a very minimal experience. And one that
really helped him, he had to take his time to find the correct key and this
really aided in his learning the spelling. Often an overload of stimuli can
cause a freeze in learning, and this is exacerbated by modern tech. The 
Amiga provides a working environment that is visual quiter and less 
disracting than modern devices.

If you have a child with LD and they struggle with reading and writing, sit
them down in front of an Amiga and see what happens, it just might surpise
you!

 
@endnode
@node amiga2023 "Amiga in 2023"
@toc articles 
============================================================================
@{b}Amiga in 2023@{ub} - by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

By the time you are reading this it is either near the end of 2023 or it is
already 2024. As this is our last issue of 2023 it seems appropriate to 
look back at what happened in 2023. So grab a hot mug of tea, coffee, hot
chocolate or something with a bit more of kick and read on. But before we
get on I will mention this does not represent the Amiga community as a whole
and was gathered from people who decided to vote from AmiBay, EAB, Amiga.org
and the WhatIFF? forum poll. Some Amiga users have scoffed at the idea of
this poll and it may not be perfect but it at least give a partial view
of how people viewed 2023 regarding new hardware and software.

@{b}On to the awards ...@{ub}

2023 we had a lot of new games come out, it was probably the best year we 
have had for games in a while but WhatIFF? is not about the games, really, 
as such an informal poll was done across several Amiga forums regarding the 
best hardware and software of 2023.

@{b}In the hardware category@{ub} the resounding result was the PiStorm, this
card has taken the Amiga scene by storm (pun intended :), bringing the 
power of emulation to real hardware. WhatIFF?'s hardware of the year
award goes to PiStorm. Other hardware should get a mention as well are the
Vampire series of cards and RGB2HDMI adapters.

@{b}Software@{ub} wise the Amiga had many games released however regarding serious
software the list was much more limited and concentrated more on updates.
The software that got the most votes was Amiga OS3.2.x, below that came in
Infinity Music Player (Imp3) and IBrowse.

Finally we will look at the @{b}best Amiga vendor@{ub} of 2023, writing for WhatIFF?
requires reviewing various hardware and software as such we are ordering
from various Amiga shops and over the year have created a list of the best
vendors servicing the Amiga. For 2023, there has been one stand out Amiga
shop that has shipped their products very quickly, responses in record
time to questions, has reasonable prices and is able to respond in a timely
and polite manner to issues. Taking all of these points into consideration
the award for WhatIFF?'s best Amiga vendor of 2023 goes to: 

=> www.amigastore.eu

They have consistently provided good service and most importantly been 
helpful when issues occurred with damaged/non-working hardware. while there
are other Amiga vendors out there doing a fantastic job AmigaStore.EU has
done just that little more by having competitive prices and providing A
class service. 

Thank you to everyone who voted and gave suggestions, finally thanks must 
be given to all the hardware and software developers keeping our Amiga scene
alive and exciting. And it would be remiss of me to not to mention the 
importance and hard work of all the Amiga vendors, who are also keeping the
Amiga alive for new comers and veteran users. A happy new year and here is
looking forward to 2024!
 
@endnode

