@node andrewvaisey "Andew Vaisey Interview"
@toc talkingamiga
============================================================================
@{b}Interview - Andrew Vaisey: Spheroid@{ub} by @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

@{b}1. Hi Andy, thank you for taking the time for this interview, to begin with 
   can you tell us a little about yourself?@{ub}

My pleasure, thank you for taking an interest and asking!

I'm an almost 50 year old from Wales, UK, who has been using computers 
since he was about 10 years old, mainly various Commodore machines.  I'm a 
teacher by trade, but currently work in the family business as a manager.  
I'm happily married (Hi Chantelle, sorry you have to keep putting up with 
this Commodore @{b}thing!@{ub}), have two lovely daughters and three wonderful 
grandchildren.

I'm slowly introducing the grandchildren to the wonders of old computers and 
gaming.  My eldest grandson already has some Commodore64 testing and 
graphics credits to his name on the Commodore Scene Database (CSDb), has 
been testing Spheroid for me and recently finished his first PC game coding 
project.  The second grandson has been testing Spheroid for me and his best 
so far is level 7 and considering he has only just turned 4, that's quite an 
achievement!

@{b}2. How did you get started with the Amiga?@{ub}

After 4 years of using a Commodore64, I asked for and received an A500 (with 
the 10 Star Pack) for Christmas 1988, after being wowed by the graphics and 
sound being demonstrated on an A1000 in a local independent computer store.  
I never put my C64 away though.  My Amiga and C64 always sat next to each 
other on the desk in my bedroom when I was younger and *still* do, now I'm 
(much) older!

@{b}3. You have recently released the game Spheroid, have you created any other 
   games prior to Spheroid?@{ub}

On the Amiga, no.  I've developed and released a few games and demos on the 
C64 (which you can find on CSDb) and have a couple of unreleased games on 
the PC.  I've also contributed to other people's games and demos across 
various 8bit machines, mainly graphics and music.

@{b}4. How did the idea for Spheroid come about?@{ub}

Now that's a story!  Back in around 1988, in the days before I started 
coding seriously on any machine, I started to create a simple game where 
you guided a metal ball around a maze of coloured squares.  This was done on 
the C64 using SEUCK.

Once I had an Amiga, I bought AMOS in around 1990 (?) and set about 
recreating this maze game.  Being young, the idea was off and on for many 
years and went through numerous design changes and a swap to AMOS Pro so I 
could use the compiler.  That all finally stopped around 1993(ish), half-way 
through a major code refactoring: I had used AMOS procedures for all the 
subroutines without realising there was a limit to how many times procedures 
could be @{b}GOSUB@{ub} before a crash.

Fast forward to 2022 and after a few false starts, I finally get round to 
resurrecting my A1200 to see what remained of anything on the hard drive.  
Low and behold, it boots first time and after imaging the drive so I can 
snoop around in WinUAE, I find the Spheroid AMOS source and all the assets 
intact.  However, the code won't run as it was half-way through being 
refactored and after 30 years I didn't have a clue what I or it was doing!

However, I didn't want to waste the game design or assets so after a 
couple of days of learning Blitz Basic 2 (the game didn't need the raw speed 
of 68K), I set about recoding the game from scratch, with the main game 
engine coming together in a few days!

@{b}5. Was the game developed on real Amiga hardware or via emulation?@{ub}

Both. I don't like running my real hardware for too long these days, even 
with modern power supplies and recapped circuit boards, so most of the 
development was completed in WinUAE, with testing and tweaking on real 
hardware.  

I have my real Amiga setup "mirrored" WinUAE on my development laptop, 
except with an insane amount of RAM which speeds up development and reduces 
crashes!

I also have a RaspberryPi 3 with an Amiga system setup for additional dev 
work and testing.

@{b}6. You handled all the programming, graphics and sound, what software did 
   you use?@{ub}

For the actual game:

Ultimate Blitz Basic 2.1+ was used for code.  Graphics were drawn in Deluxe 
Paint IV and Personal Paint.  The music was written in OctaMED Pro 5.01b.  
Sound effects were grabbed with a Technosound Turbo sampler using 
AudioMaster, which also handled the sample editing as required.  A PC based 
level editor was created by Ray Lejuez, a fellow member of my scene group 
Arkanix Labs. 

Other software:
ReOrg, DOpus, IconDeluxe, VirusZ, BlacksEditor.

The loading and ending screens were created for me by Toni Galvez.  I 
believe he used ProMotion, if the comment data in the file is to be trusted!

@{b}7. What was the most challenging aspect of developing the game?@{ub}

Levels!  Game engines present certain challenges, but with perseverance, 
issues and bugs are overcome quickly.  Creating the levels is the slog and 
the challenge for me.  Keeping motivated is hard when you've done a few 
levels and realise there are 40 more to do!
                                    
@{b}8. Did you incorporate any ideas or influences from other games?@{ub}

Not really.  The main game design is completely my own.  Sure, there are 
probably "similar" games out there, but when I originally dreamt it up back 
in the late 1980s and developed it further in the early 1990s, there was no 
internet or online databases so I would have been blissfully unaware if 
there were analogous games.

If really pushed, I would probably say that the rolling ball was influenced 
by Quedex and the mine tiles by Bombuzal, both on the C64.  Some people have 
asked if the C64 puzzle game @{b}Sensitive@{ub} was an influence, but it wasn't.  
During the game design stage, I wasn{t aware of that game and the gameplay 
in Spheroid is different anyway.

@{b}9. Do you plan to release the game on other platforms?@{ub}

In time, Spheroid will be ported to the C64 (already at 20% progress) and 
the PC.  I'm handling the C64 version entirely myself.  On the PC, I'm 
handling code and music, with Toni Galvez supplying the graphics.

@{b}10. How do you start the development process?@{ub}

Jump straight in!  Whether on the Amiga or C64, once an idea gets into my 
head, I have to see it on the computer as soon as possible.  This usually 
results in a frantic couple of weeks where I focus completely on coding the 
main engine that drives the game.

That part of the process is actually the most satisfying for me, seeing what 
is possible, solving problems, finding bugs and so on.  Once the basics are 
working, I find it harder to keep up the pace with regards the content!

@{b}11. What advice do you have for other Amiga users who want to create their 
    own games?@{ub}

Coding wise, just go for it! Try starting with learning Blitz Basic 2!  When 
I first got Blitz back in the 1993, I found it quite unstable, with lots of 
crashes.  I've since realised that this was because of a lack of memory, 
even with the RAM upgrades I had at the time, and (very) numerous errors in 
the printed manual.

Running on WinUAE under KS/WB 3.1 with a 030/040 and 1Gb of RAM (impossible 
back in the day), Blitz is as stable as they come and really quite powerful!  
In addition, there are great resources online including corrected manuals 
and helpful forums and websites.

Sure, you're not going to write a Uridium 2 or Doom clone, but for most 
projects, Blitz is *more* than adequate!  It{s a great language!

@{b}12. Looking beyond Spheroid, do you have plans for other games?@{ub}

I know there are some people who are already looking for me to do a sequel 
to Spheroid on the Amiga, with improved graphics and additional gameplay 
elements.  This will probably happen once I have completed a couple of my 
C64 projects, probably happening in tandem with the PC port of Spheroid.

I'd also love to port some of my C64 games to the Amiga, including 
Chiller 2, CHILL3R, and the Lost Realms of Murkasada.

@{b}13. If you have any real Amiga hardware, what machines do you own?@{ub}

I have an A500 and two A1200s. The A500 is boxed up at my parents' house.  
One A1200 is boxed up safe under my bed and the other, set-up in my little 
development studio next to my Commodore64's.

My main A1200 has a 1230/16Mb card, a 4GB CF hard drive, an Indivision 
scandoubler/flicker fixer for HD video output and an internal Gotek floppy 
drive.  Externally connected is a Cumana floppy drive, a CD-ROM drive 
connected via a Squirrel interface and a Technosound Turbo Sound Sampler.  
There are various other bits and pieces as well, connected as required.

@{b}14. Which Amiga is your favourite and why?@{ub}

I{d have to say the A1200.

I loved my A500, but only really used it as a games machine.  Yes, I 
upgraded it with extra memory, a small hard drive and a few other bits and 
pieces, but games is all I really ever run on it.  When I started trying to 
get creative with code, graphics and music, the A500 started to run out of 
steam for me, even with the upgrades.

Once I'd got an A1200 with hard drive (and a few other bits and pieces) 
things really opened up.  The increased power and OS3.x reliability was 
great.  As well as being creative, I used it as my main machine right up 
until about 1999, completing my university degree work on it as well as 
creating classroom resources in the early days of my teaching career.  A 
VERY capable machine and still is, even to this day!

Although I've never owned them so can{t technically say they're my 
favourites, I'd love to have a big box Amiga, probably an A3000 or A4000.

@{b}15. Thank you for your time Andy and for creating Spheroid, is there 
    anything you would like to say to the Amiga community before we finish?@{ub}

Please continue supporting the Amiga scene!  By that, I mean make a purchase 
from or donation to (however small):

  * the many technical wizards who continue to design replacement parts or 
    offer repair services;
  * the numerous manufacturers and websites that still sell hardware 
    replacements and upgrades; 
  * the numerous individuals and groups still creating software, both games 
    and applications;
  * the many forums, blogs and magazines (print and online) who support users 
    and create new content. 

Without those above, there is no way I'd have been able to resurrect my 
A1200, maintain and upgrade it or begin creating on it again!  The Amiga 
really is a special computer!

@endnode

@node robcranley "Rob Cranley Interview"
@toc talkingamiga
============================================================================
@{b}Interview - Rob Cranley: DrawerGenie@{ub} by @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

@{b}1. Can you give us a brief background of your experience with the Amiga 
   programming?@{ub}

I was quite late to the Amiga, getting my first (an A1200) around 1993. 
Before that, I was using my trusty Atari 800XL, which I got when I was 8 or 
9 years old in the late '80s. I learned to program BASIC on that and the 
BBC Micro at school from the excellent Usborne computing books in the 
library, incidentally, the Usborne books are all available free now: 

=> https://usborne.com/gb/books/computer-and-coding-books 

I was also very interested in electronics, however one project I worked on 
was to add hardware to my Atari that would let it control motors and relays 
from code. Unfortunately, this damaged one of the chips in the Atari and so 
I was without a computer for a while until I got my A1200. Once I had that 
I started programming a little in AMOS, but quickly moved onto Blitz Basic. 
I also started learning C and ARexx from excellent books released by Amiga 
Shopper magazine, as well as C and QBasic on the PCs we had in secondary 
school. For me, programming was at least as important as gaming as a pastime 
and reason for having a computer.

For some time I was also coding as a part of my day job developing medical 
equipment, and that involved writing firmware for lab equipment and was 
mostly in C, but sometimes also for Windows using VisualBasic, C#, even 
Delphi at one point. But for me, I got the most enjoyment from programming 
in Blitz Basic on the Amiga, so that's what I kept doing in my spare time.

@{b}2. Is DrawerGenie your first Amiga application?@{ub}

No, I've released a few other applications too, most of which can be found 
on AmiNet. InstallerGen and SMBMounter are probably two of the most popular, 
though both are niche in their own way. Because I code mainly for fun, I 
have dozens of half-finished programs from the past 20 or 30 years. In most 
cases it's just a proof-of-concept, or a basic framework, nothing that could 
be called a finished application. I've also written a couple of games, 
mainly simple types like board games, but I brought Nivrig's excellent Dodgy 
Rocks to the Amiga using Blitz Basic.

I've thoroughly enjoyed getting involved in the recent Amiga jams hosted by 
Zooperdan: first was the Blitz Basic Game Jam, for which I and some friends 
developed WeegieNights. It was probably overambitious and didn't get 
finished in time, but still ended up 5th place in the jam despite its 
unfinished state. We still plan to finish that whenever we have time. Then 
came the Amiga Tool Jam, which wasn't Blitz Basic-specific, and DrawerGenie 
is my main entry for this jam. I also entered a second program called 
"Closer", but it's only a little joke and is rightly in the "Most Useless" 
category :)

@{b}3. Can you explain what DrawerGenie is and what makes it unique?@{ub}

DrawerGenie is a commodity, and it allows the user to attach toolbars to 
normal Workbench windows. These toolbars include a variety of functions 
accessible through icon gadgets, most of which already exist in Workbench 
in some form, but gather them neatly together for quick access at a click 
of the mouse. The intention was to add a little bit of Directory Opus-like 
functionality to Workbench; I used DOpus 5 Magellan back in the day until 
OS3.5 was released, at which time Magellan became somewhat incompatible and 
I stopped using it. Workbench had gained some more functionality, and OS3.9 
added to that, meaning that with some customisation through ARexx scripts 
and commodities, I didn't really need DOpus any more. But there are some 
very nice functions that DOpus provided that Workbench lacks, and 
DrawerGenie adds some of these. In particular, it lets the user access files 
with cut/copy/paste actions, designate a source and destination window to 
do 1-click copy and move operations, simple packing and unpacking of Lha 
files, as well as most of the standard Workbench functions like delete, 
rename, sort and so on. It's obviously inspired by Directory Opus and 
similar filemanagers, in particular the Lister commodity for OS4 that 
provides DOpus-style listers integrated with Workbench, but as far as I know 
there isn't anything quite like it for 68k versions of Workbench.

@{b}4. How did the concept/idea for DrawerGenie come about?@{ub}

I was saying before that I was a Directory Opus 5 Magellan user before OS3.5 
came about, then switched to using OS 3.5 / 3.9 with some scripts to fill in 
the gaps in functionality. But I'm also an OS4 user, and on OS4 there's a 
great commodity called "Lister", which provides DOPus 5-style listers 
directly on Workbench. This is a great compromise between replacing 
Workbench completely and not having the DOpus-style functions, and I began 
to miss a similar thing on OS3. The idea of a small helper toolbar for 
Workbench basically came from that - what if we could just have the toolbar 
from Lister but the icon layout and full integration of a normal Workbench 
window? It's an idea that had been floating around in my head for a long 
time, and I was reasonably familiar with the Workbench interface from an 
ARexx perspective, so I knew a lot of the functionality needed for such a 
toolbar was already there. But with so many other projects that I was 
working on and so little spare time, the concept just stayed parked in my 
mind for years alongside many other ideas. It wasn't until I heard about 
the Amiga Tool Jam that I finally decided to put some time aside and develop 
DrawerGenie.

Originally it was called DrawerCompanion, which was a terrible name, but 
described how it worked in my mind - a companion window that followed 
Workbench windows around, trying to help out when it could. I changed that 
to DrawerHelper when development started to gain momentum and my 
proof-of-concept code showed it might actually work, and I felt that was a 
slightly better name though still pretty unimaginative. It was near the end 
of the Jam that I was trying to come up with an icon for the program, and 
my wife said "Why not just call it DrawerGenie and draw a magic lamp?" And 
that's why it was renamed DrawerGenie in the final days of the Jam!

@{b}5. Why did you choose to create it for OS3.2+ and not 2.1/3.1 systems?@{ub}

Well, it will work on any OS3.5+ Workbench, which includes 3.9, 3.1.4 and 
3.2. But support for earlier Workbench versions isn't really something I 
can do because earlier versions simply lack a lot of the functionality that 
DrawerGenie uses. OS3.5 was a huge overhaul of Workbench (internal version 
44), and as well as the more obvious improvement like a new icon system, 
gave it a new API through workbench.library as well as an ARexx port for 
the first time. All subsequent versions of Workbench are based on the OS3.5 
version, and while there are minor changes and bugfixes, they all support 
the same API and ARexx port. DrawerGenie uses both the workbench.library 
API v44 and the ARexx port heavily, and simply can't work without them. 
That means to be able to do the same thing on Workbench 3.1 or earlier, 
workbench.library would have to be heavily patched to gain access to the 
internal features that are available in later versions, and that sort of 
patching, as well as risking the stability of the OS, is also beyond my 
skill level. So for the foreseeable future anyway, DrawerGenie will only 
work on OS 3.5 or newer.

@{b}6. Were there any features that you wanted to include but could not/did not 
   have enough time?@{ub}

Oh yes, many! I had a list of features I wanted to include, and worked 
through them during development. The basic core features are all there, but 
there are some features that I couldn't do. For example, I wanted the option 
to have DrawerGenie automatically attach a toolbar to a Workbench window 
when it opens (currently a hotkey needs to be pressed to attach a toolbar to 
a window), but that requires patching of the OS so DrawerGenie is aware of 
any windows being opened. That's not a thing I've ever done before and I 
wasn't able to get that feature working before the deadline, so it wasn't 
included. The other main feature I wanted to include but simply ran out of 
time, was more flexible toolbars so the user can select different styles. 
Currently this can be done by swapping in a new toolbar.iff file, but the 
palette remapping isn't handled and the size is fixed at 16x16 for each 
icon, which is quite limited. Support for different sizes of icon, and for 
the excellent AISS image library, is something I want to add in the near 
future.

@{b}7. What programming language did you use to create DrawerGenie?@{ub}

DrawerGenie was actually developed in Blitz Basic, specifically the open-
source follow-on of Blitz Basic called AmiBlitz 3. This version of Blitz 
Basic provides a much nicer environment to code in than Blitz Basic 2.1, as 
well as providing many useful includes that act as wrappers for the OS 
libraries, simplifying their use. AmiBlitz is still actively developed, and 
is very highly backwards compatible with code written for Blitz 2.1, while 
also providing some useful new features like variable declaration checking 
and enforcing, dynamically assigned list arrays, variable parameter counts 
for functions and more. However, the AmiBlitz 3 environment is also more 
demanding than the Blitz 2.1 version, and so it requires a more powerful 
Amiga. It also helps a lot to use a high resolution (e.g. RTG) screenmode 
to make full use of the AmiBlitz features. So for developing on an Amiga 
with any less than a 68030, using Blitz 2.1 (ideally the Ultimate 2.1+ 
CD image) is probably a better option. It's worth mentioning though that 
the requirements of the executables produced are the same, and depend on 
the code rather than the development environment.

For anyone interested in Blitz Basic, I have some information available at 
blitzbasic.info including example code and guides on the fundamentals of 
the language from "Hello World" up to GUI creation for system-friendly 
software and graphics handling for games.

@{b}8. Do you have plans for other software beyond DrawerGenie?@{ub}

I always have a head full of ideas for games and applications I want to 
write, as well as hardware I want to design and build. Unfortunately, I 
simply don't have enough time to pursue most of these ideas, but I always 
have a couple of projects on the go. Outside of DrawerGenie, my current 
project is Solas, a clockport card that gives the Amiga control of RGB 
lighting, fans, temperature sensors, LCD screens and more. This is a mixture 
of hardware, firmware and software development with the Amiga-side software 
also written in Blitz Basic while the firmware is written in C and assembly. 
It's nearing completion now, and once that's done I have updates to 
SMBMounter that I want to make, new features to add to DrawerGenie (and look 
into OS4 compatibility since that doesn't appear to work properly), a couple 
of ideas for games I want to write and so much more. I just need to win lots 
of money so I can give up my day job :)

@endnode

@node miguelfides "Miguel Fides Interview"
@toc talkingamiga
============================================================================
@{b}Interview - Miguel Fides: Trinity@{ub} by @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

@{b}1. Hi Miguel, thank you for agreeing to this interview, can you please 
   introduce yourself?@{ub}

Hi, I was an amiga user back in its hey day. I had an A500 and then an A4000
, which I kept using well past the Pentium PC times. I was working in a 
small computer store back then and considered PCs "just job". Since then, I 
made a career in embedded programming and left the retro scene for many 
years, until 6 years ago. I moved to the country and, as I had a lot of 
spare time, I took some broken amiga computers I had came across and tried 
to repair them as a slow hobby. My A1000 was damaged beyond repair so I 
decided to start with a full board replacement...
 
@{b}2. How did you get started with the Amiga?@{ub}

My father bought me an a500 in 1989. Some school friends got an a500 too and 
then I knew some more people that still are some of my best friends today...

@{b}3. You are working on the Trinity card, what project(s) did you work on 
   before it?@{ub}

My first retro project was the A1100 replacement board. It quickly evolved 
from a simple A500-in-A1000 form factor to a feature-rich board with some 
ideas I had (a simple scan doubler based on SRAM, an 68020 with 32 bit fast 
ram, a replacement "gary" with ide interface and, finally, an A1200 
compatible expansion slot). By the time I knew the famous Edu Arana and 
shared a lot to knowledge with brought a lot of shared small but clever 
boards we worked together. I always try to keep the look and feel of the 
first 90s hardware, so when we saw some simple 030 boards appear we decided 
to make a retro-looking 030 as cheap as possible but with the then-preferred 
expandable and "filled" look of the old days. We made the Tsunami 030. Now 
we have lots of parallel projects, not enough time to complete them in 
reasonable time.

@{b}4. Why did you decide to create the Trinity card?@{ub}

When I was testing had the Tsunami boards in the A1100, I had some tricks 
in the A1100 board which made debugging of accelerators a lot easier and I 
had two spare 060 chips with I had in a (failed) accelerator project for 
A500 so I took a newer approach to an accelerator with was not the simple 
way I had used in the Tsunami. I planned an 040-PCI/PCI-Amiga double bridge 
where I could try additional hardware with DMA and designed a board which I 
could fit and test in the A1100 (and A1200 later). I called it "Trinity" 
because the dual-bridge plus FPGA. 

@{b}5. What unforeseen hurdles/difficulties have you encountered during 
   development?@{ub}

Well it's by a large margin the most complex retro project I've done. There 
are lots of difficulties which make it somewhat similar of a small embedded 
SOC of today, centered on a state-of-the-art 90's CPU instead of a todays's 
32bit core. We have DMA both in SDRAM and to-from Amiga. Some processing 
possible inside of the FPGA and peripherals for i2s (audio), i2c (which is 
used for an audio mixer), spi (this is issued for FPGA self upgrade), etc.  

@{b}6. What aspects have been easier than you had anticipated?@{ub}

Well, easier than anticipated, I can't remember none right now...

@{b}7. There are many new accelerators available for the A1200 now, what sets 
   your card apart from the others?@{ub}

As I said before, there are the requirements that I like to keep in every 
project: keep the look and the feeling of true retro hardware and maximize 
the performance of whatever is is really in the board. We don't use higher 
integration or manufacturing technology. We use the building blocks which 
were used in the 90s, no newer CPUs while bringing the highest performance 
from old stuff available. In addition to that, we sport full DMA 16/24 bit 
audio in/out with mixer (AHI). 

@{b}8. The PiStorm is one card that has become very popular, why did you choose 
   to create a card that uses a real 040/060 instead of the cheaper 
   Raspberry Pi or FPGA?@{ub}

Well, it's my personal view of retro. For this kind of board, I'm not 
looking for for maximum raw performance. I want to see my 040/060 run faster 
than ever. If there is no old hardware involved then it's in a different 
league, closer to my PC or a Pi running UAE...

@{b}9. The onboard sound card is a very unique idea, what made you decide to 
   include a sound card instead of RTG graphics?@{ub}

Back in the day I had a Cybervision 64 in my A4000, and I agree that it was 
very useful and many thought that it was the path to go. Looking back I 
think that a powerful CPU driving a frame buffer makes all contenders equal, 
not what the Amiga was in its glory days. I know that the Amiga video 
capabilities are very limited compared to retargetted graphics but, hey, 
this is retro, I was looking to faster A1100/1200, and A1100 isn't even AGA 
and it's okay. Maybe we (will) end up adding some video output but its not a 
priority for me.

@{b}10. Are there any additional features you hope to add in the future?@{ub}

Well, I'd like to add some sort on expansion slot like we did on the Tsunami 
but we have other issues before we can release the board for more testers.

@{b}11. Which type of user are you targeting the card at?@{ub}

I think that the board is a nice-looking card which feels and looks retro
Amiga that provides the highest performance. We put our soul into it and 
everybody should be able to enjoy it.

@{b}12. What has the response been like from the Amiga community?@{ub}

Well I get a lot of positive feedback from all the boards I've done. There 
are a lot of Amiga active users and collectors and a big part of them seem 
to share our view of function, quality and good-looking (hardware) that we 
try to put in our designs.

@{b}13. Do you have plans to develop hardware for other Amiga models or 
    computers?@{ub}

We have a lot of prototypes that comprise all the Amiga models. Most of them 
are due to (the) clever view of Edu and we usually share resources to help 
bringing the project forward. As I said, we can't do them all so we focus 
on a single project to finish when possible.

@{b}14. How do you see the Amiga scene developing in the next 5 years?@{ub}

I think that we are in a new time of expanding possibilities brought both by 
new performance levels for classic Amigas and new developments of system 
software. They both help to brings back the focus to native development on 
the Amiga. Thats really exciting to me because that makes the Amiga somewhat 
more appealing for what I like. I hope that more development in the 
high-performance 68k Amigas and more available development tools pave the 
way for more actually used Amigas both for gaming and native development, 
thus more new hardware diversity and refinement.

@{b}15. Being an Amiga user, do you have many Amigas, if so which one is your 
    favorite and why?@{ub}

I try to have at least one of every Amiga model and I almost have, even if 
some are not 100% good looking or complete. My favorite, of course is my 
A1000 with the A1100 replacement board and Trinity 060 because it's custom 
made to my preferences :)

I happen to have my original A4000/CyberStorm060 too, but I don't use it as 
often because I don't have much space for it.

@{b}16. Thank you for your time, before we finish do you have any final words or 
    requests to the Amiga community?@{ub}

I'd like to share the good emotions that we have got in the recent years. We 
all have some sort of nostalgia but with the Amiga we have achieved great 
success in bringing the system back to use and enjoyment.

@endnode

